The regular mysql functions, except I made a wrapper for mysql_query to abort on an error, so I don't have to type that every time. But my wrapper explicitly allows you to use the regular mysql_query function if you want. I hate wrappers that hide the underlying system.<p>I don't wrap the mysql_fetch* functions because that slows them down (lots of string copying). Plus, they don't need it.<p>I also like:<p><pre><code>  function ms($string) {
    return "'" . mysql_real_escape_string($string) . "'";
  }
</code></pre>
Very helpful for preventing sql injections, it's so short to type that I always remember to use it. And by including the quote marks right in it I don't have to go nuts escaping the quotes in the outer query.<p>If you use mysqli you don't need this - use bind variables instead.
